{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d97f89a-d665-4dec-9da5-d4e9a8432920","content":"Here are **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n### 1. 🔴 File I/O During Evaluation (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions with file I/O execute during evaluation — every single build, IDE load, and design-time build. Move this to a target so it only runs during actual builds.\n\n### 2. 🔴 Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree**. If this repo grows to include `node_modules`, `.git`, or large asset folders, evaluation time will balloon. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or add exclusions via `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. 🟡 Chained Import Depth (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. At 3 levels this is modest, but this pattern scales poorly. Consider flattening or consolidating if these grow.\n\n**Highest-impact fix:** Remove the `File::ReadAllText` call — it forces disk I/O on every evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e5051fd-75b6-412d-9295-bf10374b8efb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **File I/O property function**: `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` - This performs file I/O during evaluation, which is expensive.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern**: `**\\*.*` - This is a very broad glob that will walk the entire directory tree including potentially large directories like `node_modules`, `.git`, etc. The exclude only covers `bin` and `obj`.\n\n3. **Deep import chain**: level1.props → level2.props → level3.props - A 3-level deep import chain. While 3 levels isn't terrible, it's a pattern that can grow and become problematic.\n\n\nThe main culprits are the file I/O happening at evaluation time and the overly broad glob pattern that's scanning unnecessary directories. I should focus on optimizing these two areas first since they'll have the biggest impact on build performance.","outputTokens":532},"id":"2928c83d-2da1-4fea-8ddc-509545002823","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:09:43.962Z","parentId":"3e62b6e5-734d-4643-9133-1330297ee080"}
